courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course, students should be able to:
1. know basic biochemistry, molecular biology, and physiology;
2. recognize the structures of the human body and recall their general functions;
3. appreciate the sophisticated structure-function relationship of the human body and the integrated functions of different body parts; and
4. understand the basics of homeostatic control mechanisms that maintain normal body functions and give rise to disease states under derangement.

By the end of this course, student should be able to:
• describe public health domains and social determinants of health;
• understand the scope of public health with illustrated examples in infectious disease, environmental health and non-communicable diseases;
• work collaboratively on topical public health issues;
• describe and articulate current global health problems and their determinants;
• appreciate the complexities of issues encountered in healthcare settings and the importance of professionalism;
• apply bioethical principles and theories in analyzing contemporary public health problems;
• demonstrate ethical argumentation in a logical and coherent manner;
• describe how emerging technology and AI are used in medicine and healthcare; and
• demonstrate proficiency in clinical skills to meet the needs of clients receiving intramuscular and subcutaneous injections.
